This executive order, issued on July 19, 2017, establishes the Presidential Advisory Council on Infrastructure in the Department of Commerce. The council will consist of up to 15 members appointed by the President, representing various infrastructure sectors such as real estate, finance, construction, communications and technology, transportation and logistics, labor, environmental policy, and regional and local economic development. The council's mission is to study and make recommendations to the President regarding federal government funding, support, and delivery of infrastructure projects in sectors such as surface transportation, aviation, ports and waterways, water resources, renewable energy generation, electricity transmission, broadband, pipelines, and more. The council will prioritize the nation's infrastructure needs, accelerate pre-construction approval processes, develop funding and financing options, increase public-private partnerships, improve procurement methods, and promote advanced manufacturing and infrastructure-related technological innovation. The Department of Commerce will provide administrative support to the council, and the council will submit a report containing its findings and recommendations to the President. The council will terminate on December 31, 2018, unless extended by the President. The executive order emphasizes cooperation and information sharing among executive departments and agencies, and it does not create any legally enforceable rights or benefits.